article.headline: Connecticut 76, Holy Cross 42
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Holy Cross conceded the perimeter to
top-ranked Connecticut, and the strategy worked when the Huskies
struggled to hit their outside shots.

But the scrappy Crusaders couldn't contain UConn's inside game,
and center Jessica Moore responded to her coach's challenge with 17
points and a career-high 14 rebounds to lead Connecticut to a 76-42
win Sunday.

"It was important for her to have a big game after the game she
had the other night," UConn coach Geno Auriemma said. "She wasn't
very happy with her effort against Florida State."

Moore was coming off a nine-point performance in UConn's 81-53
win over the Seminoles on Tuesday.

"I'm just trying to bear down and get focused on what I need to
do as an individual player, whether it's on offense or defense,"
Moore said.

Moore, a 6-foot-3 junior, helped the Huskies (3-0) outscore the
Crusaders 40-14 in the paint, and her first field goal of the game
was the first 3-pointer of her career.

"I was wide open and I had the confidence in myself. I just
nailed it," Moore said.

The Crusaders stayed close for the first 12 minutes, thanks to
eight points from center Lisa Andrews, Moore's defensive
assignment. Auriemma then called a timeout and challenged his post
player.

"He told me to start playing and get focused," Moore said. "I
hadn't noticed that the girl I was guarding had scored some points
on me."

When the team returned from the timeout, Moore helped turn
UConn's five-point lead into a blowout, scoring eight points in a
17-4 run that made it 42-19 at the break.

Diana Taurasi added 16 points for the Huskies, snapping an
eight-game streak of reaching at least 20 points, and Barbara
Turner scored 14.

Lisa Andrews led Holy Cross (3-2) with 14 points.

The Huskies struggled from the field early in the second half,
missing their first eight field-goal attempts, a drought Moore
ended with an inside jumper.

Jessica Conte's 3-pointer with 12:51 left in the game got the
Crusaders within 48-32, but they never got closer. Maria Conlon hit
a 3-pointer on the next possession to start a 13-0 run by UConn.

"You always have to prevent their runs," Holy Cross coach Bill
Gibbons said. "The stars need to be aligned and everything needs
to work to try and steal one from UConn. We just didn't take care
of the ball and didn't get back on defense."

The Huskies finished with a season-low nine turnovers and made
12 steals, led by Ann Strother's career-high five.
